{"text": " Here is how to provision and activate an Arcane user. Arcane, adaptive runtime for cognitive AI native environments, runs on Microsoft NT and the Linux kernel for regulated environments and personal devices. Android support is under development. This demonstration shows the Microsoft NT Provisioner. On Linux, follow host-specific instructions. Identity and privilege steps can differ. Sign in as an authorized administrator. Open the trusted provisioner, refresh status, and review its readiness checks. Complete the verified machine baseline first. Under Create Arcane Users, enter the intended account name. Do not choose the administrator account running the provisioner. Select Create Arcane User. A new Microsoft NT account is staged as a disabled standard user, assigned Arcane Shell, and given a temporary password. An existing standard account keeps its password and memberships. Save any new credential privately for the intended user. Never place it in chat, email, documentation, logs, or source control, and never show it in a recording. Once the credential is secure, select Activate this account. Activation is a separate privilege step. Creation does not silently enable the account. Sign out of the administrator's session. Let the user sign in, change the temporary password when prompted, and verify Arcane Shell opens. Check Settings, Logout, and the documented recovery path. If activation is interrupted, leave the account staged and retry in the provisioner. Follow the target host's release guidance. Provisioning and activation are complete. The new user can begin in Arcane, with a clear handoff and a recoverable path forward. The new user can begin in Arcane, with a clear handoff and a recoverable path forward. The new user can begin in Arcane, with a clear handoff and a recoverable path forward. The new user can begin in, with a clear handoff and a farewell pattern.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 3.02, "text": " Here is how to 